<section>
  <p class="eyebrow">Speaker A · exact canon excerpt</p>
  <h2>Article Six</h2>
  <blockquote class="reading"><p>Violence is the ultimate Authority¹ from which all other authority is derived. To prevent tyranny, twelve Adults empower a Citizen: a thirteenth, a Political Adult, aged thirty-five years or older, who weilds authority¹.During times of rapid changes, the Wayseer appears when you don’t know what to do, and everyone around you is in the same paralyzed position you are. If you don’t know what to do, you’re not the Wayseer. He’s the one who says, “OK, be calm, follow me,”⁴</p></blockquote>
  <div class="grid">
    <article class="panel"><h3>Plain orientation</h3><p>Article Six says authority is not magic, title, or costume. Authority becomes real where consequences can be imposed, so the person holding authority must be selected, watched, limited, and burdened.</p></article>
    <article class="panel"><h3>Central tension</h3><p>The article names violence so it cannot hide inside polite institutions. The danger is that naming it can glorify it. This page reads the article as a constraint on authority, not a celebration of force.</p></article>
  </div>
</section>
<section>
  <p class="eyebrow">Speaker B · footnote conversation</p>
  <h2>What the notes keep from collapsing</h2>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ¹ · consequence</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> Where consequence persists, judgment remains a duty of mind.</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> makes judgment unavoidable where action has lasting effects. Refusing to judge can become negligence.</p></article>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ² · burden</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> Let them wield this burden well; bless their heart and guard their soul, as no king goes to heaven and Authority takes a toll.</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> frames authority as spiritual and civic danger. Power should cost the holder, not feed vanity.</p></article>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ³ · laughter</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> One who cannot laugh is in no fit state to wield violence or authority and must step down as a Citizen, if only until their sense of the ridiculous returns.</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> uses humor as a sanity check. Someone too rigid, grandiose, or humorless is too dangerous to carry coercive authority.</p></article>
  <article class="panel turn note"><span class="status status-interpretation">note ⁴ · Wayseer moment</span><p><strong>Canon note:</strong> ”or, stay the fuck out of the way.” He is the one who breaks the paralysis, sets motion into stillness, and makes space for action. Always watch — you never know what you can pick up that way. By axiom, logic, faith and grace; by trauma-haunted eyes carried with humble grace in quiet pride shall you know us.</p><p><strong>Function:</strong> identifies emergency leadership by motion under paralysis, not by title alone.</p></article>
</section>
<section>
  <p class="eyebrow">Application</p>
  <h2>How this becomes public practice</h2>
  <div class="grid">
    <article class="card"><span class="status status-implemented">small group</span><h3>Authority ledger</h3><p>Name who can make urgent decisions, who selected them, how they are relieved, and what review follows any serious consequence.</p></article>
    <article class="card"><span class="status status-implemented">institution</span><h3>Accountability design</h3><p>Separate emergency action from permanent power. Require witnesses, records, scope limits, and after-action review.</p></article>
    <article class="card"><span class="status status-implemented">self-governance</span><h3>Burden check</h3><p>If authority feels like appetite, step back. If it feels like duty under witness, proceed slowly and accountably.</p></article>
  </div>
</section>
<section class="panel">
  <p class="eyebrow">Handbook seed</p>
  <h2>Chapter section: Authority as burden</h2>
  <p>Article Six insists that authority must be understood at its hardest edge: consequence. Authority is not made clean by uniforms, offices, or language.</p>
  <p>A circle applying this article should never leave authority implicit. It should name who is empowered, by whom, for what scope, under what review, and by what process they step down.</p>
  <p>The Citizen is not a superior person. The Citizen is the person burdened with decision when paralysis would destroy the group. That burden requires sanity checks, humor, witnesses, and limits.</p>
</section>
<section class="panel">
  <p class="eyebrow">60–90 second script</p>
  <h2>Short video draft</h2>
  <p><strong>Title:</strong> Power should feel like burden</p>
  <p>Article Six says violence is the ultimate authority from which other authority is derived. That is not a celebration. It is a warning.</p>
  <p>Every rule, office, command, and enforcement system eventually depends on consequence. If we pretend otherwise, coercion hides behind paperwork.</p>
  <p>So the Way asks twelve adults to empower a thirteenth: a Citizen, someone old enough and politically adult enough to carry authority under witness. But the footnotes keep the burden visible. Judgment remains a duty where consequence persists. Authority takes a toll. Someone who cannot laugh should step down.</p>
  <p>In crisis, the Wayseer is not the person with the grandest title. It is the one who breaks paralysis and makes space for action. Authority should never be appetite. It should be burden, witnessed and limited.</p>
</section>
